// Global mai this ki valau = > window
// function mai this ki valau = > window
// es5(mean normal function) function inside obj = object
// es6(arrow function) function inside obj = window
// es5 function inside es5 function inside obj = window
// es6 function inside es5 function inside obj = object


JavaScript mein this ka behaviour call ke tarike par depend karta hai.
🟦 Global scope mein this hamesha 🟩 window ko point karta hai, aur 🟦 normal ES5 function ko agar directly call karo toh usme bhi this = 🟩 window hota hai.
Lekin jab 🟧 ES5 function object ke andar method ke form me likha ho, aur aap usse obj.method() ke saath call karte ho, tab this us 🟩 object ko point karta hai.
Wahin 🟪 arrow function (ES6) ka apna koi this nahi hota, isliye object ke andar arrow method likhne par bhi this hamesha 🟩 window hota hai.
Agar aap 🟧 object → ES5 function → ES5 function ka deep nested structure banate ho, toh inner ES5 function ka this phir se 🟥 window ho jata hai, kyunki call ke time woh object se bind nahi hota.
Lekin agar structure 🟧 object → ES5 function → 🟪 arrow function ka ho, toh arrow function apne outer ES5 function ka this inherit karta hai, isliye woh 🟩 object ko hi point karta hai.
💡 Simple rule: Arrow functions = parent ka this ES5 methods = jis object se call hua uska this normal functions when loosely called = window.



