✔ Inside normal function (non-strict mode)

Browser:

function test() {
  console.log(this); // window
}
test();


Node.js:

function test() {
  console.log(this); // global object (but NOT {})
}
test();

Browser me this = window, Node.js me this = {} (global scope me).



..................................call,apply,bind......................
call() kisi function ko turant execute karta hai aur this ko manually set karta hai.
Arguments comma-separated diye jate hain.

Example:
function introduce(hobby, city) {
  console.log(`Hi, I am ${this.name}. I like ${hobby} and I live in ${city}.`);
}

const user = { name: "Rahul" };

introduce.call(user, "Cricket", "Delhi"); 
// Output: Hi, I am Rahul. I like Cricket and I live in Delhi.
show.call(obj, a, b, c);



Definition:
apply() bhi function ko turant execute karta hai aur this set karta hai,
but arguments array ke form me deta hai.

Example:
function introduce(hobby, city) {
  console.log(`Hi, I am ${this.name}. I like ${hobby} and I live in ${city}.`);
}

const user = { name: "Rahul" };

 introduce.apply(user, ["Football", "Mumbai"]);
 // Output: Hi, I am Rahul. I like Football and I live in Mumbai.
show.apply(obj, [a, b, c]);



Definition:
bind() function ko turant execute nahi karta,
yeh ek new function return karta hai jisme this permanently set hota hai.

Example:
function introduce(hobby, city) {
  console.log(`Hi, I am ${this.name}. I like ${hobby} and I live in ${city}.`);
}

const user = { name: "Rahul" };

 const boundIntroduce = introduce.bind(user, "Gaming", "Bangalore");
boundIntroduce();
// Output: Hi, I am Rahul. I like Gaming and I live in Bangalore.
let newFn = show.bind(obj);
newFn(); // call later



